qplot(x = price, data = diamonds, color=I("#414141"), fill=I("#0641c8")) + 
  facet_wrap(~cut, scales="free_y")

##### Now the graphs indicate that the distributions are similarly distributed.

Bivariate Analysis

Create a scatterplot of price vs x.

ggplot(aes(x=x, y=price), data = diamonds) +
  geom_point()

The scatterplot has several outliers with x values of 0. Generally, as the value of x increases past 6, the price increases exponentially.

Now, I find the correlation between price and each of x, y and z.

cor.test(diamonds$x, diamonds$price, method = 'pearson')
##

  geom_point()

Yuck! Letâ€™s prevent some of the overplotting so we might be able to see a trend.

ggplot(aes(x=depth, y=price), data = diamonds) +
  geom_point(alpha=1/100)

We can see from this plot that most diamonds have depth values between 60 and 64.

cor.test(diamonds$depth, diamonds$price, method = 'pearson')

Now I plot price vs.Â carat.

ggplot(aes(x=carat, y=price), data = diamonds) +
  geom_point(alpha=1/10) +
  xlim(0, quantile(diamonds$carat, 0.99)) +
  ylim(0, quantile(diamonds$price, 0.99))
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 926 rows containing missing
## values (geom_point).

I will create a new variable to represent the volume of the diamonds. This variable is calculated by multiplying the x, y, and z variables. Then I plot volume vs.Â price.

diamonds$volume = diamonds$x * diamonds$y * diamonds$z

ggplot(aes(x=volume, y=price), data = diamonds) +
  geom_point(alpha=1/20) +
  xlim(0, 800)
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 3 rows containing missing values
## (geom_point).

Letâ€™s find the correlation between price and diamonds with a volume between 0 and 800.

custom_volume = subset(diamonds, diamonds$volume > 0)
custom_volume = subset(custom_volume, custom_volume$volume <= 800)
cor.test(custom_volume$volume, custom_volume$price, method = 'pearson')
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  custom_volume$volume and custom_volume$price
## t = 559.1912, df = 53915, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.9222944 0.9247772
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9235455

The correlation between volume and price in the original data is 0.90 and subsetting some of the outliers increased the correlation to 0.92. Now I plot it and add a linear regression line.

ggplot(aes(x=volume, y=price), data = custom_volume) +
  geom_point(alpha=1/20) +
  xlim(0, 500) +
  ylim(0, 20000) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', color='red')
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 14 rows containing missing
## values (stat_smooth).
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 14 rows containing missing
## values (geom_point).
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 10 rows containing missing
## values (geom_path).

This doesnâ€™t look like a good fit at all. The linear model line entirely misses what may be an actual linear relationship for prices under 8000 and volumes under 180. Letâ€™s zoom in further to see if this data is approximately linear in that range.

tiny = subset(diamonds, diamonds$volume > 30)
tiny = subset(tiny, tiny$volume <= 180)

ggplot(aes(x=volume, y=price), data = tiny) +
  geom_point(alpha=1/20) +
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', color='red')
